{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_myrtle_ver01/data/56022775/00541313400/1949062001/0130.xml":{"full_text":"Biz Snubs Workers in Profit Grab\nUtilities Boys\nAttack Public\nPower Program\nGE\u2019s Charles Wilson\nSays Recession Is\n\u2018Good for Country\u2019\nATLANTIC CITY Big\nchiefs in the nation\u2019s private\npower industry\u2014nearly 3,000\nstrong went into a battle\ndance at a powwow here and\npledged to hack away at pub\nlic power development which\nwould benefit the country\ngreatly.\nThe public power program\nis high on the list of Presi\ndent Truman\u2019s goals and long\nhas been advocated by the\nBrotherhood.\nElmer L. Lindseth, Cleveland\npower executive, told the represen\ntatives of the $17,500,000,000 pri\nvate power industry at the con\nvention of Edison Electric Insti\ntute that utilities men must start\na \u201cgrass roots campaign\u201d to con\nvince the American public of the\nability of \u201cbusiness-managed power\ncompanies to satisfy the country\u2019s\npower demands.\u201d\nNamed president of EEI, Lind\nseth asserted the industry will\nsound public under\n\u201cdevelop\na\nstanding by use of all channels of\ninformation to employes, neigh\nbors and customers.\u201d\nMorris Sayre, chairman of Na\ntional Association of Manufactur\ners, was quick to rush to Lindseth's\nside to add his support.\nCorporation heads in the manu\nfacturing and utilities industries\nSayre spouted, must give their 12\nmillion employes \u201cthe economic\nfacts of life to offset collectivist\npropaganda.\u201d\nExpansion Plans \u2018Sufficient\u2019\nWhile admitting that expansion\nplans of the private industry are\nmoderate, the private power big\nshots had the gall to say they were\nsufficient.\nCharles E. Wilson, General Elec\ntric prexy, assured the utilities\nboys that the drop in industrial\nproduction now under way will\ncut into the public\u2019s demand for ex\npansion of power facilities.\nHe said that the downward trend\nwill continue until the last quar\nter- of \u201950 when production will be\n15 per cent below the \u201948 average.\nThen, he continued, it will start\nupward again, reaching 1918 lev\nels by the end of 1951.\nA little recession will be good for\nthe nation, the GE president as\nserted.\nHe said that the electric indus\ntry will cut consumers\u2019 goods pro\nduction 20 per cent and industrial\nproduction 10 per cent by the end\nof \u201949.\nWants Promise Kept\nMINNEAPOLIS Labor was\npromised Taft-Hartley repeal and\nit wants just that.\nC. E. Scheer, secretary of Foot\nboard Lodge 804, made it clear in\na recent telegram to Sen. Hubert\nHumphrey.\nHe wired the Minnesota Demo\ncrat that the \"Democratic Party\npromised repeal of Taft-Hartley\nand return to Wagner Act. Labor\nexpects this promise to be ful\nfilled without capitulatory com\npromise and amendment. We are\nnot only opposed to the name\nTaft-Hartley.\u201d\nSAN ANGELO, Tex. Field\nSupervisor J. T. Choyce addressed\na special meeting of Lodge 837\nrecently, explaining rights and\nprivileges of members under Rail\nroad Retirement Act. Choyce made\na highly informative speech, re\nports George W. Privett, publicity\nchairman.\nL H. Meehan was\nPEORIA, Ill.\npresented a 45-year pin recently\nby Lodge 27.\nENDS 47-YEAR RUN ON CANADIAN PACIFIC\u2014Fellow workers, railroad officials and friends\nwere waiting at the station to greet F. J. Hawkins, member of Lodge 223, Winnipeg, Man., since 1903,\nas he stepped off the Winnipeg Beach train to end 47 years of Canadian Pacific service. Here Haw\nkins, right, receives a gift presented by J. E. McNerney, 223 president and local chairman, from BRT\ners and fellow employes. Hawkins' three sons, H. H., L. H. and C. F., are also CP employes and\ntogether the four have 126 years of CP service to their record. F. J. Fryer and J. L. Hall, superintend\nent and assistant superintendent, respectively, of Portage Division, were among the railroad officials\nwho congratulated the veteran Brotherhood member on his retirement.\nAMA Is Still Fighting\nTruman\u2019s Health Plan\n(Continued from Page 5)\nbeing that of a doctor holding the\nhand of a sick child, as he takes\nits temperature with a worried\nand nearly crying mother looking\non.\nNo mention is made of the fact\nthat doctors are injecting politics\ninto the picture by aiding the distri\nbution of this propaganda to pa\ntients in hospitals and offices, thus\nturning a professional call into a\ncheap demonstration of barroom\npolitics;\nWhile the august new York\ntimes paternally compliments the\nmedicos for their adoption of a\n\u201cnew policy\u201d \u201cwhich is more\nin keeping with the medical needs\nof this industrial day,\u201d it also notes\nthat \u201cThe resolutions do not go\nnearly as far as many reformers\nwould have them.\u201d\nThe only thing wrong with the\nstatement is the word \u201creformers\u201d\n\u2014it isn\u2019t reformers who would\nhave the AMA go farther, but the\npeople, and their representatives,\nas is attested by the groups back\ning the Truman program for na\ntional health insurance: AFL, CIO,\nBRT and the standard railway labor\norganizations, Consumers Union,\nAmerican Veterans Committee, In\nternational Association of Machin\nists, Americans for Democratic Ac\ntion and the National Farmers Un\nion.\nAMA Black Mark\nAnother black mark\nagainst\nAMA is the history of the group\u2019s\naction in opposing any advance in\nmedical aid for any group.\nThis\nrecord was cited before a House\nsubcommittee by CIO Secretary\nTreasurer James B. Carey:\nYears ago, AMA opposed for\nmation of community boards of\npublic health and was against com\npulsory reporting by physicians to\na public body on communicable\ndiseases.\nIn 1921 it violently opposed fed\neral grants-in-aid to public health\nagencies.\nWhen National Tuberculosis As\nsociation was organized to deal\nwith the disease as a national prob\nlem, it was initially opposed by\nAMA.\nThru the years, AMA has con\nsistently opposed group practice\nof medicine thru voluntary organ\nizations of citizens and local phy\nsicians.\nThe Mayo Clinic had to fight\nAMA to establish itself.\nAMA opposed Workmen\u2019s Com\npensation, designed to protect\nworkers in industry.\nIn 1929 it opposed government\nmedical care for veterans suffering\nfrom illness not service-connected.\nIn 1932 it denounced all group\npractice as c\nor social\nistic.\nIn 1934 it opposed Blue Cross\nhospitalization plan, and several\nyears later was indicted in Federal\nCourt in Washington under anti\ntrust laws for its tactics in oppos\ning formation of the Group Health\nAssociation.\nIn 1948 the AMA House of Dele\ngates rejected a proposal by Blue\nShield and Blue Cross to work out\na combined medical and hospitaliza\ntion plan for voluntary groups.\nThe convention action of AMA\nin retreating on a few minor points\nof its stand against progressive\nmedicine has not covered its record\n\u2014which the word \u201coppose\u201d charac\nterizes\u2014nor has it obscured pres\nent plans to scuttle the Truman\nplan for a national health insurance\nlaw.\nThe situation is a little better,\nbut the fight will be tough with\nthe AMA dragging weight astern.\nRailroad Fair\nNearly Ready\nCHICAGO\u2014As June 25, open\ning date for the Railroad Fair, ap\nproaches, a small army of men\nand mechanized equipment has en\ntered the final stages of polishing\nup, announced Major Lenox R.\nLohr, Fair president.\nMost exhibits undergoing con\nstruction changes are from 75 to\n90 per cent completed already.\nThe last spike has been driven\nin the relaying of several miles of\nstandard gauge track, a thousand\nnew seats have been added to the\n\u201cWheels\na-Rolling\u201d\npageant\ngrandstand, and frameworks are\nrising for the last of the new\nstructures for the 1949 edition of\nthe Fair.\nOver 4,500 gallons of gaily hued\npaint cover the exhibits.\nEDWARDSVILLE, ILL. Mrs.\nGussie Johnson, fifth vice-presi\ndent, assisted in initiating eight\nnew members of LA Lodge 908\nrecently and was honored the same\nday at dinner with the officers of\nthe lodge. Also taking part in the\ninitiation ceremonies were Ernest\nine Kirk, president; Fern Colcal\nsure, past president; Jeannette\nGericke, vice-president; Kathryn\nWadsworth, secretary; Margaret\nStafford, treasurer; Hazel Sexton,\nconductress;\nAgnes Donaldson,\nwarden; Iona Baker, chaplain;\nLaura Burhan and Dorothy Pratt,\nguards. An orchid corsage was\npresented Mrs. Johnson.\nIn unity there is strength. At\ntend lodge!\nSong and Poem\nAre Composed\nFor 105 Fete\nOIL CITY, Pa. A song\nand a poem, especially written\nfor the recent 64th anniver\nsary dinner of Oil Creek\nLodge 105, evoked much\npraise from the 125 guests\nfor the composers.\nThe song, \u201cMemories of\nHome,\u201d was written by Dick\nWard and played and sung\nfor the first time by Joe Ken\nnedy and Curly Wolford.\nWard, a retired Pennsy con\nductor who spends his winters\nin the South, has been a mem\nber of 105 over 37 years.\nThe poem, \u201cDaddy\u2019s Or\nder e d,\u201d was composed by\nLucy Eddinger, 16-y ear-old\ndaughter of R. L. Eddinger, a\nValley brakeman and member\nof 105. Lucy, a student at\nCranberry High, has had\nmany of her poems published\nand favorable comments re\nceived from well-known poets.\nWill Clair, a 50-year BRT-er,\npresented a 40-year pin to John\nMoffatt, a conductor in Oil City\nyards.\nGeorge Corbitt, who has been\nretired five years, received his 35\nyear pin from Pat Walsh, also a\nBrotherhood member 50 years.\nMovies, \u201cUnfinished Rainbows,\u201d\n\u201cSteel\u2014Man\u2019s Servant,\u201d and \u201cThe\nShining Mountain,\u201d were shown.\nJoe Kennedy, local pianist and\n105 member, led community sing\ning.\nKennedy \u201crattled the ivories,\"\nWilbur Schwabenbaur (105) han\ndled the drums and Curly Wolford\nwas singer and master of cere\nmonies.\nThe committee in charge extends\nthanks to the following for help\nin making the 64th anniversary\ncelebration a great success:\nMiss Martha Steirs, Mrs. Jerry\nMealey and Joe Kennedy, all of\nOil City; Mrs. Hazel Jawdy and\nM. Wolford, Franklin; Oakwood\nRose Gardens, Oliver Brothers and\nthe local Eagles.\nHome for Aged Income\nHIGHLAND PARK. III. \u2014Fol-{\nlowing contributions were received\nI\nat Home for Aged and Disabled\nRailroad Employes of America,\nreports J. L. Smedberg, manager:\nDiv. 271 GIA to BLE_$10.00\nInterest _\nSale of old grease,\npapers and junk\n12.50\n5.55\n$28.05\nConducts \u2018Cold\nWar\u2019 Against\nThem: Murray\nCIO Chieftain Says\nPlacing Blame Easy\nIf Depression Comes\nCHICAGO Drawing his\nbead on two targets, equally\ndangerous to the American\nway of life, Philip Murray,\nCIO president, singled out for\nassault in an address here:\nRapacity\nbusiness.\nin\nAmerican\nCommunism in trade\nunions.\nMr. Murray charged that\nAmerican business in waging\na cold war against the Amer\nican people in its lust for\nenormous profits at the ex\npense of the working man and\nwoman who, he said, could\nhardly purchase the necessi\nties of life.\nThe CIO leader addressed 500\ndelegates and alternates attending\nthe convention of Communication\nWorkers of America (CIO).\n\u201cI contend publicly for the first\ntime that American business is\nconducting a cold war against the\nAmerican people. That statement,\nno matter what the economists\nhave to say about it, no matter\nwhat the newspapers and trade\nmagazines have to say about it, is\nbased on fact.\u201d\nPresident Murray asserted that\n\u201cif you have a depression in the\nUnited States of America, or vast\nunemployment, this year or next\nyear, it will come to you as a re\nsult of ugly, hypocritical manipu\nlation of powerful business and\nfinancial interests in the United\nStates.\nA depression is not war\nranted now by the conditions.\u201d\nAssails U. S. Steel\nThe CIO leader directed the\nreal \u201cheat\u201d of his attack against\nthe mighty U. S. Steel Corp.\nIn the last six years, Murray\nsaid, U. S. Steel spent $750 million\nin improvement of plant, facilities\nand equipment\u2014all taken from\ncurrent earnings\u2014and had written\noff $125 million to $140 million a\nyear in depreciation losses to its\nplant.\nGood business, indeed, he said.\n\u201cThe community should know,\u201d\nMr. Murray asserted, \u201cthat this\nwealthy corporation now pays its\naged workers an overall pension\namounting to $5.83 a month.\n\u201cIt should shock the community\nto know that this huge institution\nhas the effrontery to send each\nworker at retirement a letter wish\ning him \u2018long, happy\u2019 retirement.\n\u2018Long and happy\u2019 on $5.83\nmonth!\u201d\na\n(The pension goes to persons 65\nyears of age who have 25 years\nof service with the company.)\nIt\u2019s \u2018Brutality\u2019\n\u201cThe (U. S. Steel) charges for\ndepreciation each year amount to\nmore than U. S. Steel has\u2019 paid\nout in pension for the last 10\nyears.\n\u201cYou would naturally conclude\nthat a human being is entitled to\nas much consideration as a ma\nchine, wouldn\u2019t you?\nIs that giv\ning consideration to social\nsponsibility\nre\nThat\u2019s brutality.\u201d\nOn the Commie issue, President\nMurray said he would recommend\nto the CIO convention this fall an\namendment to the constitution\nbarring\nunions from\nCommunist dominated\n\u201crepresentation on\nthe CIO (executive) board or in\nour CIO councils.\"\nThere is no place in the CIO,\nMr. Murray said, \u201cfor those who\nplace loyalty to the Communist\nParty above loyalty to the CIO\nand the labor movement.\u201d\nHave you suffered an injury at\nwork? Give all details promptly\nto your lodge secretary so he may\nreport the injury to Grand Lodge.","height":"20604","width":"14084"}}
